<section id="methodology" class="paper-col py-10">
  <p class="section-num">3 &middot; Methodology</p>
  <h2>Agent Design &amp; ML Pipeline</h2>

  <h3>3.1 ReAct Decision Process</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The agent follows a deterministic 7&#8209;step procedure encoded in its system prompt. Each
    step either invokes a tool or produces the final structured answer.
  </p>

  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-6 space-y-1.5 text-[1rem]">
    <li><code>lookup_bin</code> &mdash; resolve eligible schemes, dual&#8209;brand flag, domestic hint.</li>
    <li><code>get_scheme_status</code> &mdash; for each eligible scheme, exclude disabled.</li>
    <li><code>get_scheme_auth_stats</code> &mdash; pre&#8209;seeded historical auth rate (7d / 30d).</li>
    <li><code>estimate_interchange</code> &mdash; ML inference per enabled scheme.</li>
    <li>Score each scheme (formula below); apply adaptive weights if high&#8209;risk.</li>
    <li>Rank, pick the winner, build <code>fallback_chain</code>.</li>
    <li>Emit strict JSON with rationale and full score breakdown.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="bg-rule/40 border border-rule rounded-md p-5 my-6 font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed">
score = (auth_rate_7d &times; w<sub>auth</sub>) &minus; (interchange_pct &times; w<sub>ic</sub> / 100)
<br/><br/>
Default weights&nbsp;&nbsp;: w<sub>auth</sub>=0.60, w<sub>ic</sub>=0.40
<br/>
High-risk weights: w<sub>auth</sub>=0.75, w<sub>ic</sub>=0.25
<br/><br/>
High-risk iff &nbsp;amount &gt; 1000&nbsp; OR&nbsp; cross_border == true
  </div>

  <h3>3.2 Tool Contracts</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Tools are exposed to the Converse API as JSON Schema definitions. The agent receives typed
    inputs and structured outputs &mdash; not free&#8209;form prose &mdash; which keeps the
    reasoning grounded in deterministic services.
  </p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-rule text-left">
          <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Tool</th>
          <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Backed by</th>
          <th class="py-2 font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Returns</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="align-top">
        <tr class="border-b border-rule/60">
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-[12.5px]">lookup_bin</td>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">DynamoDB <code>BIN_Table</code></td>
          <td class="py-3 text-muted">eligible_schemes[], card_type, card_product, issuer_country, dual_brand, domestic_scheme</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-rule/60">
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-[12.5px]">get_scheme_status</td>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">DynamoDB <code>Scheme_Config</code></td>
          <td class="py-3 text-muted">enabled (bool), display_name</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-rule/60">
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-[12.5px]">get_scheme_auth_stats</td>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">DynamoDB <code>Auth_Rate_Stats</code></td>
          <td class="py-3 text-muted">auth_rate_7d, auth_rate_30d, decline_breakdown, sample_count</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-[12.5px]">estimate_interchange</td>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">S3 ONNX (XGBoost)</td>
          <td class="py-3 text-muted">estimated_interchange_pct, interchange_category, confidence, cross_border</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>3.3 ML Interchange Model</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Interchange rates are predicted by an XGBoost regression trained on synthetic settlement
    data parameterised from publicly known interchange tiers (EU regulated, US unregulated,
    AMEX premium, UnionPay domestic). The model is exported to ONNX via
    <code>onnxmltools</code> and loaded into Lambda at cold start via
    <code>onnxruntime</code>; subsequent invocations reuse the cached session.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-x-8 gap-y-3 my-6 text-[15px]">
    <div><span class="font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Training data</span> &middot; 25,000 synthetic rows, seed = 42</div>
    <div><span class="font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Features</span> &middot; scheme, card_type, card_product, mcc, amount, merchant_country, card_country, cross_border</div>
    <div><span class="font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Encoding</span> &middot; one&#8209;hot categoricals (46 features)</div>
    <div><span class="font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Algorithm</span> &middot; XGBoost, 300 trees, depth 6, learning rate 0.08</div>
    <div><span class="font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Loss</span> &middot; squared error</div>
    <div><span class="font-sans font-semibold text-accent">Tree method</span> &middot; <code>hist</code></div>
  </div>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Inference&#8209;time encoding mirrors training&#8209;time: the saved
    <code>feature_metadata.json</code> stores the encoder vocabulary so the Lambda can produce
    identical feature vectors. Unknown category values yield a zero vector for that block,
    matching <code>OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore")</code>.
  </p>

  <h3>3.4 Explainability Contract</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The agent must emit strict JSON with the following keys:
    <code>selected_scheme</code>, <code>confidence</code>, <code>rationale</code>,
    <code>fallback_chain[]</code>, <code>score_breakdown</code>. The Lambda parses and validates
    every field; malformed output is rejected, ensuring downstream consumers receive a typed
    decision object &mdash; never free&#8209;form prose.
  </p>
</section>
